 contributes to creative death are not just crippling diseases that make man defenseless in the face of death, and not just the arguably universal fear of death but, equally important, the innumerable impositions on the part of various outsiders. Many conflicts in the lives of Rylkova’s subjects arose not from their opposition to the existing political regimes but from their interactions with like-minded and supporting intellectuals, friends, and relatives. The book describes the lives and choices that concrete individuals and—by extrapolation—their literary characters must face in order to preserve their singularity and integrity while attempting to achieve fame, greatness, and success.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Jan 2023) 0aAuthors, Russiany19th centuryxAttitudes. 0aDeath in literature. 0aDeathxPsychological aspects. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Russian & Former Soviet Union.2bisacsh  aA Confession.  aAbout Chekhov.  aAnna Karenina.  aBunin.  aChekhov.  aCreativity.  aDante.  aDeath.  aGogol.  aLiberation of Tolstoy.  aMeyerhold.  aPsychology of Creative Personality.  aRussian drama.  aRussian literature.  aSustainability.  aThe Cherry Orchard.  aThe Death of Ivan Ilych.  aThe Decembrists.  aThe Kreutzer Sonata.  aThe Life of Arseniev.  aThe Seagull.  aThe Steppe.  aTolstoy.  aUncle Vanya.  aWar and Peace.  aWriter’s Block.  aanxieties.  aexistentialism.  ahypochondria.  aletters.  aliterary theory.  amortality.  apsychoanalysis.  apsychology.  athe Divine Comedy.  awriting.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAcademic Studies Press Complete eBook-Package 2020z978311068820708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus PP Package 2020 Part 2z978311069629508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLET